irst registration for a race, I noticed that I should change from unspecific training to specific training.\n<div>\n<div>\n\nThen I bought the book<a href=\"http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/1934030198?ie=UTF8&amp;tag=tricassoforen-20&amp;linkCode=xm2&amp;camp=1789&amp;creativeASIN=1934030198\" target=\"_blank\"> \"the training bible\"</a> by Joe Friel and read more about endurance sports. I summarized the basic terms here. If I got your interest, buy this book and read yourself.\n\n<strong>Systematic training</strong>\n\nmeans that you follow a training schedule which should be based on approved training principles. Furthermore it should include your individual needs of your own body. The TriCoreTraining online coach for runners, bikers and triathlon athletes follows these principles:\n<ul>\n	<li>With each workout you should achieve something specific</li>\n	<li>You should improve continously and don\'t try to increase in big steps</li>\n	<li>Recovery is a important element to give your body the possibility to increase</li>\n	<li>Less is more - too much training is not good for growing your muscles</li>\n</ul>\nWhy should you train? You stress your body and the next time you become fitter. One training principle is the principle of stepwise over loading (no excessive over loading - this harms your body). A repeating over compensation leads to a better fitness through the right load at the right time.\n\nMore training principles:\n<ul>\n	<li>Training should be specific (that means a run workout helps your running and a bike workout helps your biking)</li>\n	<li>The benefit of a workout is reduced if you decrease frequency, duration and intensity and the effect of short time workouts disappears faster than from long time workouts</li>\n	<li>Training is indiviual (you can\'t take the training schedule of another athlete)</li>\n	<li>You have to reach your peak for your races - we want to reach our maximum at the right time (that\'s the goal of our season). Before a race we reduce the load (by 20-50% - tapering), because our body reacts 10-21 days after a workout.</li>\n	<li>Recovery is the key to a better performance</li>\n</ul>\nSome other essential terms for your training:\n<ul>\n	<li>Frequency\nHow often i.e. per week you should train. Some studies say that 3-5 times per week are perfect but for an Ironman this is not enough.</li>\n	<li>Duration\nHow long should be single workout? Only long workouts aren\'t useful, also shorter, more intensive workouts are important. Your longest workout should be as long as your longest race.</li>\n	<li>Intensity\nIntensity is not easy to measure. How stressfull is a workout for you? We use intensity zones for that based on heart rate zones. That\'s why we need a heart rate monitor.</li>\n	<li>Volume\nVolume is calculated by duration x frequency, i.e. 3x1 hour = 3 hours volume.</li>\n	<li>Workload\nis calculated by multiplying frequency, duration and intensity.</li>\n</ul>\nThe TriCoreTraining system is based on the well-known training system of \"periodization\" (also known as cyclization) (since 1940). Your body is repeatly confronted with load and relief. Big advantage of this system which is in use for more than 70 years and is not changed in its core. It\'s medically approved. For hobby athletes a proportion of 3:1 established. Three weeks of load followed by one week of recovery. This is also valid for your training week and the containing workouts - three days of load and one day of recovery.\n\nBut how to divide our training year? There are different phases and we\'ve got a goal for each cycle.\n\nThe macrocycle is the training year itself. You divide your year in regard of your main competitions. All workouts will be planned based on the main races (that\'s the reason why you should define competitions). The next cycle is the mesocycle - the division of your training year in phases - beginning from general training to specific.\n\nHere are the phases of mesocycle:\n<ul>\n	<li>the general preparation phase (PREP, BASE)</li>\n	<li>the specific preparation phase (BUILD)</li>\n	<li>the race phase (PEAK/RACE)</li>\n	<li>the transition phase / recovery phase (TRANSITION)</li>\n</ul>\nThe BASE-BUILD-PEAK-RACE phases (main training period) last on average for 12 to 21 weeks. Depending on your sport goals (Ironman, Marathon, Sprinttriathlon, etc.).\n\nThe microcycle relates to the planning of your week, how each workout during a week is placed.\n\nThe training system also takes special needs of the athlete into consideration:\n<ul>\n	<li>Endurance</li>\n	<li>Strength</li>\n	<li>Speed</li>\n</ul>\nThese three corners of your training programme are based on the training principles of specialisation, so you need different training units to fullfil different needs of your body.\n\nNow you might understand that such an electronic training system needs a lot of knowhow and it took more than one year to develop TriCoreTraining and to react on different requirements and delivers you an optimal training programme.\n\n</div>\n</div><!--:--><!--:de--><p>\n<div>\n<p>Als ich 2003 mit meinem Triathlon-Training begonnen habe, habe ich mich noch nicht mit den grundlegenden <strong>Begriffen des Trainings</strong> befat. Wozu auch? Ich wollte nur Sport machen. Aber irgendwann, besonders wenn man sich dann zu Wettkmpfen anmeldet, merkt man, dass man von einem unsystematischen Training zu einem systematischen Training bergehen sollte.</p>\n<p>Da habe ich mir dann das Buch <a href=\"http://www.amazon.de/gp/product/3936973512?ie=UTF8&amp;tag=trico-21&amp;linkCode=xm2&amp;camp=1638&amp;creativeASIN=3936973512\">\"Die Trainingsbibel\" von Joe Friel</a> gekauft und mich in die (Un-)Tiefen des Ausdauersportstrainings eingelesen. Diese grundlegenden Begriffe will ich hier kurz zusammenfassen. Wenn ich damit dein Interesse wecken kann, dann kauf dir bitte das Buch und lies mehr darber!</p>\n<p><strong>Systematisches Training</strong></p>\n<p>bedeutet, dass man einem Trainingsplan 